      <hedline>
        <hl1>Letting Off Steam</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Cheryl Hoff letter corrects Jonathan Reynolds' July 9 Food column on what constitutes barbecue sauce in eastern North Carolina</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>As a recent transplant to North Carolina, I haven't yet reached native fluency in the language of barbecue. But I know enough to know Jonathan Reynolds (Food, July 9) got it wrong: here in eastern Carolina, barbecue means a vinegar-based sauce, served in bottles filled with hot peppers. It's those apparently misguided people in the western part of the state who use a tomato base. He is, of course, invited down any time he wants to learn this in person.</p>
        <p>Cheryl Huff  Oriental, N.C.</p>
      </block>
